Preheat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Cut the @butternut squash{600%g} in half lengthways 
and scoop out the seeds with a #spoon{} (or a #melon baller{} works well if you have 
one!). Slice it widthways to about 1cm thick (we want to be able to cook this nice 
and quickly). Now chop into 1cm cubes.

> Risotto is the ultimate comfort food; it's warm, creamy and satisfying. With 
> just the right amount of heat from the chillies, creaminess from the risotto 
> rice and the roasted butternut squash, you'll be cosying up on the couch to 
> enjoy this bowl of goodness. Don't forget the all important final squeeze of 
> lemon!

Put your butternut squash on a #baking tray{} and drizzle over some @oil{}, a 
sprinkling of @salt{} and a good grind of @black pepper{}. Pop in your oven on 
the top shelf for ~{25-30%minutes}. Then remove from your oven and keep to the 
side.

Meanwhile, cut the @onion{1} in half through the root, peel and chop into ½cm 
pieces. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch}. Cut the @red chilli{1/2} 
in half lengthways, remove the seeds and finely chop. Peel and grate the 
@garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Cut the @streaky 
bacon rasher{4} into 1cm wide strips (use #scissors{} for this if you want, it's 
much easier!). Grate the @parmesan cheese{40%g}.

Put a #saucepan{} of @water{1000%ml} on to boil with the @vegetable stock pot{1} 
and stir to dissolve.

Put half the @unsalted butter{30%g} in a large saucepan on medium heat along 
with a drizzle of @oil{}. Add your onion and bacon and cook for ~{5%minutes} 
until your onion is soft and your bacon browned. Add your chilli (add less if 
you don't like spice) and garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Once the pan is smelling fragrant and garlicky, add the @risotto rice{175%g} along 
with a good pinch of @salt{} and a good grind of @black pepper{}, stir and cook 
for ~{1-2%minutes} until your rice looks slightly translucent around the edges.

After a minute or two, add in a ladle of your stock, stir, and once absorbed, add 
another ladle of stock. Keep the pan on medium heat and continue adding stock 
(stirring now and again while it cooks), letting it absorb before adding another 
ladle. This should take ~{17-20%minutes}. Your risotto is ready when your rice 
is 'al dente'.

> Tip: 'Al dente' simply means the rice is cooked through but has a tiny bit 
> of firmness left in the middle.

Once cooked, remove from the heat and add your butternut squash along with three-quarters 
of your parmesan, your remaining butter and three-quarters of your parsley. Squeeze in 
half the @lemon{1/2}, taste and add more lemon juice, salt and black pepper if necessary.

Serve your risotto in #bowls{} with the rest of your parsley and parmesan sprinkled 
over the top.